  "text": "'Notch-ON' signaling may be relevant to cell fate choices because while Hes1 targets are not known in detail, TF binding site overrepresentation analysis (PWMEnrich; [CITATION_1] of Tfcp2l1 bound peaks demonstrated neighboring Tfcp2l1 and Hes1 binding sites, as well as combinatorial binding of Tfcp2l1-Foxi1-Hes1 (Figure 8-figure supplement 1) raising the possibility that Hes1 signaling in PCs may negatively modulate Tfcp2l1 and Foxi1 targets. Hes1 might repress IC genes in PC cells by enhancing chromatin modification enzymes since the inactivation of histone methyltransferase Dot1l appeared to convert PCs into ICs [CITATION_2] . In sum, Notch signaling might antagonize Tfcp2l1 in PC cells where Notch activates Hes1.",
